label chapter12:

    # [Scene: Voss Marine Solutions Headquarters | Midday]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense BGM — fast, insistent strings under a steady electronic pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant wind hitting the quay; the subtle hum of projection equipment; the occasional metallic creak of the building.]
    "You already know the shape of this room before you step in: too clean, every surface calibrated to reflect control. It makes your boots feel heavier on the polished floor. You smudge the salt on your"
    "jacket cuff without thinking, an instinctive mark of territory — a human stain on their stainless shine."
    show amaya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "Thank you for hosting us. We appreciate the time."
    show corinne_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    corinne_voss "We appreciate the willingness to talk, Ms. Reyes. Voss only moves when it meets measurable protection and regional benefit. Today's proposal is a pilot model—raised quay segments, modular aquaculture units, and co-funded marsh restoration led by TideLab."
    "The rendering blooms in the air: a model coastline with a polished quay, neat blocks of aquaculture pens, then — unexpectedly — a ribbon of green kicking against the edge: marshland stitched into corrals of engineered oyster beds. For a heartbeat something like hope flares."
    "You feel Luka's hand brush yours under the table. His fingers are warm; he doesn't pull away. The contact steadies you, and also sharpens everything else — the stakes, the temptation."
    show tamsin_cho at center:
        zoom 0.7

    tamsin_cho "We set constraints. Municipally, we need assurances on displacement, on environmental review, and a clear timeframe for the pilot's reassessment. Voss has agreed, in principle, to co-fund TideLab sensors—your small-tech network, Mr. Maren."
    hide amaya_reyes
    show luka_maren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    luka_maren "In principle is a start. Those sensors would give us real-time data across the marsh edge. We could prove efficacy."

    corinne_voss "We want to scale what works. We don't build forever; pilots inform broader deployment. The sooner we protect vital infrastructure—the ferry hub, the secondary road—the fewer people suffer long-term."
    "You watch the presentation and force your voice to stay clear, the way you learned to in public meetings: precise, not pleading."
    hide corinne_voss
    show amaya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "We need binding oversight. A community board with veto on relocations, line-item funding for TideLab's equipment and training, and legally enforceable timelines for reassessment before any permanent construction."
    hide tamsin_cho
    show corinne_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    corinne_voss "Binding is feasible when it's proportionate. But you must understand municipal timelines and funding cycles. Indefinite community vetoes can delay protection and increase risk. We propose mediation language: dispute resolution, escalator clauses, and relocation carve-outs for 'at-risk zones.'"
    "The phrase 'relocation carve-outs' lands like a stone. Your chest hardens."
    hide luka_maren
    show abuela_rosa at left:
        zoom 0.7

    abuela_rosa "I have pulled nets from water with hands that knew the bay when it was kinder. We are not numbers to be moved for the sake of a map. If the plan means neighbors become stories, then I will not bless it. But I also know when water comes and takes more than pride."
    hide amaya_reyes
    show tamsin_cho at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tamsin_cho "Pilot language is the crux. If the municipal code doesn't limit the pilot's duration and scope, a private actor can argue that successful elements justify permanence. The 'pilot' could become the precedent. We need sunset clauses, adjudicated reassessment, and escrow funding for community relocation assistance — should relocation be unavoidable."

    corinne_voss "Legally, that slows the process. Escrow is an admission of displacement risk. We can structure conditional payments tied to performance thresholds that, frankly, reduce moral hazard."
    "The phrase sits heavy; you picture people in town."
    hide corinne_voss
    show luka_maren at center:
        zoom 0.7

    luka_maren "This could let us prove the model to other towns. With Voss backing—"
    hide abuela_rosa
    show amaya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "With Voss backing comes control. 'Prove the model' has become code for 'let us do it at scale, on our terms.'"

    luka_maren "That's cynical, Amaya. Data powers policy. If the sensors show marsh restoration reduces storm surges, we win arguments later."

    amaya_reyes "But winning arguments 'later' means people get moved now. We can't treat names on my ledger as variables in an experiment."
    "The exchange is small, but it draws lines. Luka's jaw tightens; his hands flex on the controller. His temptation to accept the scale of Corinne's resources is a raw, visible thing — hope mingled with fear of failing without it."
    hide tamsin_cho
    show corinne_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    corinne_voss "No one wants relocation. That's why we invest in marsh and quay together. We can stage construction to minimize displacement. Our engineering team has phased plans."
    hide luka_maren
    show tamsin_cho at center:
        zoom 0.7

    tamsin_cho "Phases don't protect neighborhoods from legal exposure. If 'minimize' isn't defined, you'll be left with subjective judgments."
    "A heated silence. The AR rendering spins to a close-up of a street in Marisol, and the label 'Phase 2 — At-Risk Zones' pulses red. Your stomach drops."
    hide amaya_reyes
    show abuela_rosa at left:
        zoom 0.7

    abuela_rosa "I have pulled nets from water with hands that knew the bay when it was kinder. We are not numbers to be moved for the sake of a map. If the plan means neighbors become stories, then I will not bless it. But I also know when water comes and takes more than pride."
    "Her words are not a simple yes or no. They are a memory and a warning. You feel the gravity of living on a shoreline that has always demanded trade-offs — shelter for someone, exposure for another."

    menu:
        "Tighten the language: demand explicit sunset clauses and community veto":
            "You press your palms into the table and outline exact phrasing: three-year sunset, adjudicated review, escrowed relocation funds with community oversight. Tamsin nods, impressed. Corinne's smile thins; she asks for legal review."
        "Appeal to compromise: ask for staged funding with immediate sensor deployment but defer contentious clauses to legal drafting":
            "You suggest a middle path: sensors deployed now, a staged funding release tied to milestones, and a legal drafting session next week. Corinne agrees in principle; Tamsin warns of loopholes. Luka exhales, hopeful but wary."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue to the following narration"
    "The room thrums with pressure. You can feel your pulse in your temples. Each suggested clause you make is countered, reshaped, reframed — a negotiation that eats away at certainty. High arousal reverberates through your body:"
    "quick breath, damp palms, the tightness that means making a decision that will weigh on you in the years to come."

    corinne_voss "Here is a firm timeline we can agree on today: Phase One — sensors and marsh pilot within six months; Phase Two — quay segments within eighteen months contingent on marsh metrics. If TideLab indicators meet thresholds, we proceed. If not, we halt. All parties sign an MOU today; the detailed contract follows."

    tamsin_cho "An MOU isn't a binding contract. The municipal code requires a permit and a judicially enforceable agreement for any relocation. An MOU that punts core decisions to later litigation is a liability."

    corinne_voss "Legal teams can draft enforceable terms. We are offering to underwrite TideLab equipment now. We are offering community jobs, technical training, and a cooperative wetland model in our public materials."
    "You hear your own name in the sentence about 'underwriting' as if TideLab were a line item instead of a living thing. Your chest tightens until it hurts. The room presses inward — glass walls and a sky that looks like a bruise."
    hide corinne_voss
    show luka_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    luka_maren "Amaya. If we get the sensors, the data will be undeniable. We can build a case that marsh works and stop further destructive walls. This is leverage."
    hide tamsin_cho
    show amaya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "Leverage only works if we are able to wield it. If they control the timeline and the legal language, leverage is a story we tell later — while people get moved now."
    hide abuela_rosa
    show tamsin_cho at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tamsin_cho "Can Voss agree to escrow funds managed by an independent trustee appointed by the community? Can we have third-party auditors on the metrics?"
    hide luka_maren
    show corinne_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    corinne_voss "Escrow isn't the problem. Trustee selection and audit criteria are. We can agree to auditors with joint nomination, provided their remit is scientifically validated and not motivated by local politics."
    "Your internal monologue snaps like a brittle reed. 'Not motivated by local politics' is a polite way of saying the elders' testimony could be discounted as parochial. You can feel the town's pulse in your mouth — angry, frightened, trusting you to keep them whole."
    "You swallow responsibility, the old reflex. The weight of every face in your ledger presses into your jaw. You can feel how close you are to nodding. It would be a rational, pragmatic nod: accept limited risk for massive resources. But the rationality tastes of salt and erosion."
    "Abuela Rosa watches you still, the shawl folded like a harbor. Her hands rest in her lap — patient, waiting. Her look is neither approval nor condemnation; it is a tide waiting to break. You must decide how to hold the town against that pressure."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings accelerate, electronic pulse quickens — the room seems to pulse with urgency]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant gull, thin and high; the AR projector clicks as the timeline advances.]
    "Your voice tight, you try to find the right words to keep both promise and people intact."

    amaya_reyes "We can do this. But only with clear, enforceable, independent oversight frameworks spelled out today. No ambiguous 'pilot' language that allows permanent creep. Escrow with community trustees. Sunset clauses. Binding audit protocols. And a clause that any relocation must pass a judicial standard and community consent."

    corinne_voss "Those terms are... exacting, Ms. Reyes. They will complicate deployment timelines."

    tamsin_cho "They also protect the town."
    "You feel all the air leave the room when Corinne lifts her chin and sits down at the table. Her fingers steeple in a gesture that underlines the moment: business resolve meeting community demand."

    corinne_voss "We will take your proposed language to legal. We can begin drafting with those as a basis. Voss wishes to be a partner, not an antagonist. But understand—the longer negotiations drag, the longer high-risk infrastructure is exposed. We will not be patient indefinitely."
    "The phrase 'not be patient indefinitely' is a deadline wrapped in threat. Your heart spikes. The pressure is a physical thing now, like tidewater pressing against a seawall. You feel the decision perched at the edge of something sharp."
    hide amaya_reyes
    hide tamsin_cho
    hide corinne_voss

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A single, sustained note — the highest point before a fall]
    "You can sign an MOU today that begins sensor deployment and starts funding TideLab — a small, immediate victory with strings that could tie you later. You can push for legal terms now and risk losing"
    "the resources while fighting in courts. Or you can walk away, preserving autonomy but forfeiting the leverage and funding you could use to protect lives."
    "You sense Luka's breath behind you—hope, fear, the magnet of what could be. Abuela Rosa's complex gaze feels like a hand on your shoulder, both steadying and heavy."
    "Your lungs burn. Your mind catalogues the costs: lives, livelihoods, trust. The room waits. The projector ticks. Outside, the bay presses at the quay in patient insistence."
    # [Page-Turn Thought]
    "You picture the ledger again — names of people who have pinned their futures to you. You imagine telling Mateo and Mrs. Calder that the town chose prudence over resources; you imagine telling them you took"
    "the offer and lost their homes to a clause no one read. The sound of a gull cuts through the thought like a warning call, and for the first time in a long time, you recognize"
    "that any choice will fracture something you love."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    jump chapter15
